            <h2 class="mt-0">Executive Summary</h2>
            <p>The global trading architecture has undergone profound transformations over the past two decades. The proliferation of multinational corporations, the fragmentation of production into global value chains, and rapid technological diffusion have fundamentally altered how nations interact economically. This research essay investigates a central question: Does the classical theory of comparative advantage, developed by David Ricardo over two centuries ago, still explain modern trade patterns?</p>
            <p>Utilizing export data from the World Bank and UN Comtrade projected through 2025, this analysis employs the Revealed Comparative Advantage index and the Trade Specialization Index to evaluate the export portfolios of India, Brazil, Germany, and Portugal. A longitudinal comparison of India and Brazil from 2000 to 2025 further isolates the impact of hyper-globalization on structural specialization.</p>
            <p>The findings indicate that countries continue to export products in sectors where they possess a comparative advantage. Modern trade data shows substantial evidence supporting Ricardo's foundational proposition. However, the nature of this specialization has shifted. Rather than specializing entirely in final goods, modern economies increasingly specialize in specific tasks and intermediate components within broader value chains. The evidence demonstrates that while globalization has altered the mechanics of trade, the underlying gravitational pull of relative opportunity cost remains the primary determinant of national export structures.</p>

            <h2>Introduction</h2>
            <p>International trade is the metabolic system of the global economy. Understanding why nations export specific goods while importing others is critical for formulating industrial policy, designing tariffs, and anticipating labor market disruptions. In 1817, David Ricardo introduced the principle of comparative advantage, positing that trade is driven by differences in relative opportunity costs rather than absolute efficiencies. According to Ricardo, even if one nation is less efficient at producing all goods compared to a trading partner, mutually beneficial trade is still possible if each nation specializes in the sector where its relative inefficiency is lowest.</p>
            <p>Despite its mathematical elegance, the enduring relevance of comparative advantage remains vigorously debated. Skeptics argue that modern phenomena have rendered classical models obsolete. Capital is highly mobile, technology diffuses instantaneously, and multinational firms internalize cross-border trade, seemingly bypassing the traditional state-centric boundaries assumed by early economists. The rise of global value chains means that a smartphone assembled in one country contains components from dozens of others, complicating traditional metrics of national specialization.</p>
            <p>The objective of this research is to rigorously test the traditional Ricardian proposition against contemporary data. By examining four distinct economic profiles, India as a services and pharmaceutical exporter, Brazil as a resource-abundant agricultural powerhouse, Germany as an advanced manufacturing hub, and Portugal as a diversified European economy, this essay evaluates whether actual trade flows align with theoretical predictions.</p>

            <h2>Literature Review & Theoretical Framework</h2>
            <p>The intellectual lineage of trade theory begins with Ricardo's formulation of opportunity cost. His model relied on differences in labor productivity across nations as the sole driver of trade. In the early 20th century, Eli Heckscher and Bertil Ohlin expanded this framework. The Heckscher-Ohlin model proposed that comparative advantage arises not just from labor productivity, but from differences in factor endowments such as land, labor, and capital.</p>
            <p>More recently, the Global Value Chain literature pioneered by Richard Baldwin has reshaped how economists view specialization. Baldwin argues that the "second unbundling" of globalization allowed the geographic separation of factories. Consequently, nations no longer specialize in industries but in specific tasks within an industry.</p>
            <p>To empirically measure unobservable comparative advantage, economists rely on Revealed Comparative Advantage. Developed by Bela Balassa, the index assumes that true comparative advantage will manifest in actual post-trade data. The formula is defined as:</p>
            
            <div class="formula-block">
                RCA<sub>ij</sub> = ( X<sub>ij</sub> / X<sub>it</sub> ) / ( X<sub>wj</sub> / X<sub>wt</sub> )
            </div>
            
            <p>Where X<sub>ij</sub> represents the exports of product j from country i. X<sub>it</sub> represents total exports from country i. X<sub>wj</sub> denotes the total world exports of product j, and X<sub>wt</sub> represents total world exports of all goods. An RCA value greater than 1 indicates that the product's share in the country's export basket is higher than its share in global trade, revealing a comparative advantage.</p>

