            <h2>Synthesis of National Profiles</h2>
            
            <h3>The Knowledge Pivot versus Reprimarization</h3>
            <p>Reviewing the data above, <strong>India</strong> presents a highly distinct manifestation of comparative advantage. Unlike the traditional East Asian development model which relied heavily on labor-intensive manufacturing, India leapfrogged into complex services and specialized pharmaceutical production. Despite massive absolute volumes of machinery exports, the RCA for machinery is below 1. This perfectly illustrates Ricardo's core thesis. India exports machinery, but its true relative strength lies in the high-RCA service sector.</p>
            
            <p>Conversely, <strong>Brazil</strong> offers a textbook example of Heckscher-Ohlin dynamics operating within a Ricardian framework. Its comparative advantage is deeply rooted in natural factor endowments: vast arable land and rich mineral deposits. An RCA over 30 for soybeans indicates that soybeans are thirty times more prevalent in Brazil's export basket than they are in global trade. The data unequivocally supports the proposition that Brazil's integration into global markets is driven by its resource-based opportunity costs.</p>

            <h3>Acquired vs. Inherited Advantage</h3>
            <p><strong>Germany</strong> demonstrates comparative advantage driven by human capital, accumulated engineering knowledge, and dense industrial clusters. It represents advanced manufacturing specialization. Germany relies on a unique ecosystem of vocational training, specialized mid-sized firms, and deep supply chain integration across Central Europe. Germany has effectively ceded low-value manufacturing, reallocating labor and capital to sectors where its opportunity cost is lowest.</p>
            
            <p><strong>Portugal</strong> serves as an excellent case study of a mid-sized European economy navigating the pressures of the single market. It exhibits a bifurcated comparative advantage. It holds a massive naturally endowed advantage in cork, dominating the global market. Concurrently, integration into European value chains has fostered an acquired comparative advantage in automotive assembly and parts manufacturing.</p>
        </article>

